    <h1>The se&#xAD;cret su&#xAD;per&#xAD;power of com&#xAD;post</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The com­post from food waste can be turned into fer­tiliser. But the liq­uid from the com­post, called "Bokashi tea" can do more - apart from be­ing a nu­tri­ent-rich fer­tiliser, it can be used to un­clog drains. Even if it can­not be eaten, un­wanted food can be trans­formed into some­thing use­ful.</p>
    <p>The av­er­age house­hold in Sin­ga­pore throws about $258 worth of un­eaten food a year. The Sunday Times gets to the bottom of the is­sue and raids fridges to see how some homes are re­duc­ing waste, or mak­ing bet­ter use of it.</p>

